## Implementation Notes

Emit only the first value, then complete.

### Approach
```rust
pub trait FirstExt<T>: Watchable<T> {
    fn first(&self) -> Cell<T, CellImmutable>
```

### Key Implementation Details
- Use `Arc<AtomicBool>` to track "emitted" state
- On first emission, emit value, set emitted=true
- Ignore all subsequent emissions
- Optionally signal completion (needs rx3-0tw)

### Implementation
```rust
let emitted = Arc::new(AtomicBool::new(false));
self.watch(move |value| {
    if !emitted.swap(true, Ordering::SeqCst) {
        derived.notify(value.clone());
        // TODO: signal completion, unsubscribe
    }
});
```

### Note
This is essentially `take(1)` - consider making it an alias:
```rust
fn first(&self) -> Cell<T, CellImmutable> {
    self.take(1)
}
```

### Files to Create/Modify
- Create: `src/traits/first.rs` (or add method to TakeExt)
- Modify: `src/traits/mod.rs`

### Test Cases
- Verify only first value emitted
- Verify subsequent values ignored

description:
CRITICAL: Derived cells (from map, filter, scan, etc.) register subscriptions on parent cells but never unsubscribe when dropped. This causes memory leaks - subscriptions accumulate in parent's DashMap forever.

Example: a.map().map().map() creates 3 subscriptions in 'a' that persist even after derived cells are dropped.

Current pattern in operators:
```rust
let weak = derived.downgrade();
self.watch(move |value| {  // UUID returned but never stored
    if let Some(d) = weak.upgrade() { ... }
});
```

Need to either:
1. Store subscription ID and unsubscribe in Drop impl
2. Use weak references that parent can detect and prune
3. Implement reference-counted subscription cleanup

